Mari picks up on how Yuri's a lot like Basil: insecure, and a bit paranoid about negative evaluation. Her goal is to break through Yuri's outer shell and fear of being judged, and see what she's really like inside. Really, she wants Yuri to stop being so afraid of her-- the problem is, Mari's naturally pushy and judgemental.
As part of this, Mari might try poking holes in Yuri's "sophisticated and mature" persona, or at least try to get Yuri to reveal sides of herself that she's unprepared to show. She's trying to throw her off-balance.
Some of this might go out the window when Mari sees Yuri's scars-- she's probably going to get quite worried about Yuri-- but I haven't quite thought through how that's going to appear.
Mari likes classical music. She might be pushing her preferences onto Yuri a bit, even if they do happen to line up. (Would Yuri like to dance to a waltz with Mari?)

Notes on the overall conversation flow for these cases:
For Nagisa's stage 0, Mari will ask one of the two "Intro" question variants (depending on whether Basil is also playing).
For each of Nagisa's next two stages (1 and 2), Mari will ask one of two 'starter' questions: - One about her school ("Starter - School") - One related to the current time of day, and the day of the week (either "Weekends", "School Day", or "School Night"). (See the "School Day" case for details on how the conditions work for the latter set of questions.)
The actual order in which Mari asks these two questions is allowed to vary, for the sake of replayability. This will also allow us to add new questions for these two stages fairly easily, if desired.

"Mari", on its own, leads to a disambiguation page listing articles about various places, people, goddesses, etc.
"Mari (given name)", however, lists the possible meanings of the kanji in Mari's name, as well as a list of both real and fictional people with the first name "Mari". At least at time of writing (Nov. 2021), Mari is listed at the very bottom of the page as "MARI, in psychological horror RPG Omori" (with a link to the Omori article).
(And no, that entry was not added by me.)

The conditions for the "Bet Redux" cases are set up so that if there was a definite outcome for their last game together (i.e. the player stayed to the end), the corresponding case will always fire. However, if there _wasn't_ a definite outcome due to the player leaving mid-game, then a result is randomly made up instead (and the corresponding lines imply that the two of them continued their bet after the player left).
